JOIN NOTES
0. Once a thread is started we wait for this thread to finish by calling join() function on thread object.
1. Double join will result into program termination.
2. If needed we should check thread is joinable before joining. ( using joinable() function)

DETACH NOTES
0. This is used to detach newly created thread from the parent thread.
1. Always check before detaching a thread that it is joinable otherwise we may end up double detaching and 
   double detach() will result into program termination.
2. If we have detached thread and main function is returning then the detached thread execution is suspended.

NOTES:
Either join() or detach() should be called on thread object, otherwise during thread objects destructor it will terminate the program. 
  Because inside destructor it checks if thread is still joinable? if yes then it terminates the program.


=========================================================
std::thread::detach() - Interview Notes
=========================================================

What is detach()?
---------------------------------------------------------

detach() separates the thread from the std::thread object.

After detach(), the thread continues executing independently
in the background.

The calling thread does NOT wait for the detached thread to
finish.

Syntax
---------------------------------------------------------

t.detach();

=========================================================
Example
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <chrono>

using namespace std;

void worker()
{
    cout << "Worker Thread Started\n";

    this_thread::sleep_for(chrono::seconds(2));

    cout << "Worker Thread Finished\n";
}

int main()
{
    thread t(worker);

    if (t.joinable())
    {
        t.detach();
    }

    cout << "Main Thread Finished\n";

    return 0;
}

Possible Output
---------------------------------------------------------

Main Thread Finished

OR

Main Thread Finished
Worker Thread Started

(The detached thread may or may not finish before the process exits.)

=========================================================
Why do we use detach()?
=========================================================

• Run a background task independently.
• Main thread does not wait.
• Ownership of the thread is released.
• Useful for fire-and-forget tasks.

=========================================================
joinable() and detach()
=========================================================

There is NO detachable() function in C++.

Use joinable() to check whether a thread can be detached.**************

Example

thread t(worker);

if (t.joinable())
{
    t.detach();
}

After detach()

t.joinable();      // false

=========================================================
What happens after detach()?
=========================================================

Before detach()

std::thread object  ------>  Worker Thread

After detach()

std::thread object          Worker Thread
     (no ownership)      continues independently

=========================================================
Important Points
=========================================================

✔ A thread can be detached only if it is joinable.
✔ detach() can be called only once.
✔ After detach(), the thread runs independently.
✔ After detach(), the std::thread object no longer owns the thread.
✔ After detach(), joinable() returns false.
✔ You cannot call join() after detach().
✔ Calling detach() on a non-joinable thread throws std::system_error.

=========================================================
join() vs detach()
=========================================================

join()

• Waits for the thread to finish.
• Main thread blocks.
• Used when the result of the thread is important.

detach()

• Does NOT wait.
• Thread runs independently.
• Used for background/fire-and-forget tasks.

=========================================================
Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. What is detach()?

detach() separates the thread from the std::thread object, allowing it to run independently in the background.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What happens after detach()?

The thread continues executing independently, and the std::thread object no longer owns it.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Is there a detachable() function?

No.

C++ provides only joinable(). If joinable() returns true, the thread can be detached.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Can we call join() after detach()?

No.

After detach(), joinable() becomes false, and calling join() throws std::system_error.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. When should we use detach()?

Use detach() only for background tasks that do not need synchronization with the main thread.

=========================================================
Important Interview Note
=========================================================

• Prefer join() whenever possible.
• Use detach() only when the thread is intentionally designed
  to run independently and you do not need to wait for its
  completion.

